How To make a DOCK bugfix patch file for web release.

Descriptions of bugs fixed pre-release and thus distributed in release x go
in file new_in_6.x.txt.  The file 6.x_bugfixes.htm is for bug fix patch files
distributed post release.  This howto describes how to create those patches.

Steps

1.  Create the bug correction using the fully patched DOCK release.
    The simplest way to do that is to checkout via the release tag:

        cvs co -r dock6-7-release dock6
        mv dock6 bugfixing
        cd bugfixing/install
        ./configure (platform)
        make install
        make test >& before

    where the dock6 checkout via the release tag has been renamed to avoid
    confusion, dock6-7-release is an example release tag, and platform
    is generally the compiler used on the gold standard machine; currently,
    gnu is the platform and an OSC machine is the gold standard (for its
    machine details see install/test/KNOWN_FAILURES).  Note that some
    bugfixes may require specific platforms or configure options.  Note
    also that any existing bugfixes must be manually applied.
    Then correct the necessary source files and rebuild:

        cd bugfixing/src/(program)
        edit (buggyfiles)  # see below for alternatives
        make clean
        cd bugfixing/install
        make install
        make test >& after

    If the bug correction changes the test outputs then the change must be
    substantiated and the output patches must be included in the bugfix.
    Compare and scrutinize the before and after test results:

        diff before after

2.  Validate the bug correction on the gold standard machine if not already
    done in step 1.  Also important to include are Mac, Intel compilers,
    and possibly Cygwin.

3.  Create the bugfix. 
    The context diff's for the source files and the test output files
    will be inserted into the bugfix file (do not cut and paste these):

        cd bugfixing/
        cvs diff -c src/(program)/(buggyfiles) > /tmp/(buggyfiles).diff
        cvs diff -c install/test/(name)/(savefiles) > /tmp/(savefiles).diff

    Use an existing bugfix file as a template, e.g.:

        cd (my_dock6_trunk)/docs/bugfixes67
        cp bugfix.1 bugfix.(next)
        edit bugfix.(next)

    Update all the sections of the bugfix file, and read into the editor
    session the context diff's: /tmp/(buggyfiles).diff and
    /tmp/(savefiles).diff

4.  Test the bugfix by applying it:

        cd /tmp
        cvs co -r dock6-7-release dock6
        cd /tmp/dock6
        patch -p0 -N -r patch_rejects < (my_dock6_trunk)/docs/bugfixes67/bugfix.(next)
        cd /tmp/dock6/install
        ./configure (platform)
        make install
        make test

5.  Add the bugfix to the web index, e.g.:

        cd (my_dock6_trunk)/docs/bugfixes67
        edit 6.7_bugfixes.htm

6.  Commit the bug correction and bugfix:

        cd (my_dock6_trunk)/docs/bugfixes67/
        cvs add bugfix.(next)
        cvs commit bugfix.(next)
        cvs commit 6.7_bugfixes.htm
        cvs tag dock6-7-(next)-release

        cd bugfixing/
        cvs commit src/(program)/(buggyfiles)
        cvs commit install/test/(name)/(savefiles)

7.  In the trunk update the bugfixes section of the release notes for the
    next version:

        cd (my_dock6_trunk)/docs
        edit new_in_(6.8).txt
        cvs commit new_in_(6.8).txt

8.  In the trunk ensure that the bug correction is in place.
    Usually the debugging process occurs in the trunk.  But if not then
    sometimes applying a patch from the bugfixing branch to the trunk
    works.  Naturally the bug correction in the trunk needs to be 
    validated and committed.

9.  Update the manual and the tutorials in the trunk.

10. Contact Scott Brozell, Trent Balius, or John Irwin to post the bugfix on the web page.

        cvs diff -r HEAD -c
        patch -c -p0 -R < ../uptodatedock6/bf
